,[214,217,221],{"_":211,"xml:id":215,"ref":216},"JP","http://orcid.org/0000-0003-3819-8537",{"_":218,"xml:id":219,"ref":220},"James Cummings","JCu","http://orcid.org/0000-0002-6686-3728",{"_":222,"xml:id":223,"ref":224},"Simona Stoyanova","SS","https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3914-9569",{"_":226,"when":227,"who":228},"renumbered files, uris and references","2021-01-19","#SS",{"n":108,"url":109,"height":110,"width":111,"desc":112,"surfaceType":113},[231],{"atLeast":232,"atMost":233},38,40,[235,236,237,238,239,240],"L'année épigraphique: revue des publications épigraphiques relatives a l'antiquité romaine., 1888-","Scibona, 1971, Epigraphica Halaesina I","Manganaro, 1988, La Sicilia da Sesto Pompeo a Diocleziano","Scibona, 2008, The Epigraphs","Prestianni Giallombardo, 2012, Spazio pubblico e memoria civica. Le epigrafi dall'agora di Alesa","Prag, Tigano, 2017, Alesa Archonidea: il lapidarium",[242,243,244,245,246,247],"R46KDTZX","UISW82JC","RZSFKACR","6GFVUASD","CJISRIUV","MI64NB9L",[249,250,251,22,32,36,252,253,254,255,252,256,257,135],"isic000801","fragment of a public latin inscription",{"_":5},"halaesa","castel di tusa","italy","sicily","antiquarium e sito archeologico di halaesa","latin",[],{"title":260,"body":261,"divs":262,"editions":287,"images":297,"handnote":303},"ISic000801. Fragment of a public Latin inscription","\u003Cdiv id=\"editions\">\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag; edition source: autopsy Prag 2011.06.15\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"la\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span> [\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]CILIV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003Cbr id=\"al2-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span> [\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]R · S · P · INỌ[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag; edition source: autopsy Prag 2011.06.15\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"al1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]CILIV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al2-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]R·S·P·IN.[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"facsimile-images\">\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000801_tiled.tif\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic000801_tiled-thumb.tif\">\u003C/a>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000801.jpg\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic000801-thumb.jpg\">\u003C/a>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"apparatus\">\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>Text from autopsy\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"translation\">\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"commentary\">\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>It is not possible to know what the likely extent of the stone was, either to the left and right, or above and below the surviving text. The letters of line 1 are most likely to be part of a name: Caecilius and Acilius are the most common, but a number of other names of this form such as Lucilius, Maecilius, Otacilius, Pacilius, Precilius, and Racilius are also attested. Both Caecilius (\u003Ca href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000803\" target=\"_blank\">ISic000803\u003C/a>; RPC I, 628-629; Cic. Verr. 2.2.23) and Acilius (\u003Ca href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000804\" target=\"_blank\">ISic000804\u003C/a>) are attested at Halaesa. The abbreviation in line 2 is most easily resolved as restituit sua pecunia (“restored (x) at his own expense”), although this cannot be certain, and Scibona’s suggestion of inopia for the word that follows is certainly plausible (i.e. that the individual named in the first part of the inscription restored something – a building perhaps – at his/her own expense due to the lack of funds on the part of the town or another body or individual). Manganaro’s suggestion of incohavit is also possible, and there are few other alternatives beginning INC or INO.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> 1973.0268 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Scibona 1971 15 no.4 fig.2 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001599\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001599\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Manganaro 1988 45-46 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001427\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001427\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Scibona 2008 26 ph \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001593\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001593\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Prestianni Giallombardo 2012 181 fig.166 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001357\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001357\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Prag and Tigano 2017 no.23 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002630\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002630\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"handnote\"> \u003Cp>The letters are neatly V-cut, of wide proportions, with minimal serifs. P is open; S has a larger upper half, leaning slightly to the right. Words are separated by a comma-like three pointed serif.\u003C/p> Lines 1-2  38-40  Not measured    \u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"license\"> Licensed under a CreativeCommons-Attribution 4.0 licence. \u003C/div>",[263,266,269,272,275,278,281,284],{"id":264,"html":265},"editions","\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag; edition source: autopsy Prag 2011.06.15\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-interpretive\" lang=\"la\">  \u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span> [\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]CILIV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003Cbr id=\"al2-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span> [\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]R · S · P · INỌ[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv class=\"attribution\">Text encoding: Jonathan Prag; edition source: autopsy Prag 2011.06.15\u003C/div>\u003Cdiv id=\"edition-diplomatic\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"al1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]CILIV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al2-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]R·S·P·IN.[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>",{"id":267,"html":268},"facsimile-images","\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000801_tiled.tif\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic000801_tiled-thumb.tif\">\u003C/a>\u003Ca href=\"ISic000801.jpg\">\u003Cimg title=\"I.Sicily with the permission of the Assessorato Regionale dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana - Dipartimento dei Beni Culturali e dell’Identità Siciliana; Photo J. Prag\" src=\"ISic000801-thumb.jpg\">\u003C/a>",{"id":270,"html":271},"apparatus","\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>\u003Cspan>Text from autopsy\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>",{"id":273,"html":274},"translation","\u003Ch2> translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">  \u003C/p>\u003Cp>  \u003C/p>",{"id":276,"html":277},"commentary","\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>It is not possible to know what the likely extent of the stone was, either to the left and right, or above and below the surviving text. The letters of line 1 are most likely to be part of a name: Caecilius and Acilius are the most common, but a number of other names of this form such as Lucilius, Maecilius, Otacilius, Pacilius, Precilius, and Racilius are also attested. Both Caecilius (\u003Ca href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000803\" target=\"_blank\">ISic000803\u003C/a>; RPC I, 628-629; Cic. Verr. 2.2.23) and Acilius (\u003Ca href=\"http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic000804\" target=\"_blank\">ISic000804\u003C/a>) are attested at Halaesa. The abbreviation in line 2 is most easily resolved as restituit sua pecunia (“restored (x) at his own expense”), although this cannot be certain, and Scibona’s suggestion of inopia for the word that follows is certainly plausible (i.e. that the individual named in the first part of the inscription restored something – a building perhaps – at his/her own expense due to the lack of funds on the part of the town or another body or individual). Manganaro’s suggestion of incohavit is also possible, and there are few other alternatives beginning INC or INO.\u003C/p>  ",{"id":279,"html":280},"bibliography","\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> 1973.0268 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001283\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Scibona 1971 15 no.4 fig.2 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001599\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001599\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Manganaro 1988 45-46 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001427\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001427\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Scibona 2008 26 ph \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001593\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001593\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Prestianni Giallombardo 2012 181 fig.166 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001357\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001357\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003Cli> Prag and Tigano 2017 no.23 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002630\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10002630\u003C/a>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>  ",{"id":282,"html":283},"handnote"," \u003Cp>The letters are neatly V-cut, of wide proportions, with minimal serifs. P is open; S has a larger upper half, leaning slightly to the right. Words are separated by a comma-like three pointed serif.\u003C/p> Lines 1-2  38-40  Not measured    ",{"id":285,"html":286},"license"," Licensed under a CreativeCommons-Attribution 4.0 licence. ",[288,290,293,294],{"html":289},"Text encoding: Jonathan Prag; edition source: autopsy Prag 2011.06.15",{"id":291,"lang":135,"html":292},"edition-interpretive","\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-interpretive\">  \u003Ca id=\"al1-interpretive\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span> [\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]CILIV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003Cbr id=\"al2-interpretive\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span> [\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]R · S · P · INỌ[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>] \u003C/span>\u003C/div>  \u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>",{"html":289},{"id":295,"lang":135,"html":296},"edition-diplomatic","\u003Cdiv class=\"textpart\" lang=\"la\">\u003Cspan class=\"ab\" id=\"div-diplomatic\">\u003Ca id=\"al1-diplomatic\">\u003C!--0-->\u003C/a>\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">1\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]CILIV[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003Cbr id=\"al2-diplomatic\">\u003Cspan class=\"linenumber\">2\u003C/span>[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]R·S·P·IN.[\u003Cspan dir=\"ltr\" class=\"gap\">---\u003C/span>]\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>",[298,300],{"image":109,"thumb":299,"title":112},"ISic000801_tiled-thumb.tif",{"image":301,"thumb":302,"title":112},"ISic000801.jpg","ISic000801-thumb.jpg",[304],{"html":305},"The letters are neatly V-cut, of wide proportions, with minimal serifs. P is open; S has a larger upper half, leaning slightly to the right. Words are separated by a comma-like three pointed serif.","\u003C?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>\n\u003C?xml-model href=\"https://epidoc.stoa.org/schema/latest/tei-epidoc.rng\" type=\"application/xml\" schematypens=\